ABSOLUTE RULES:
1. NEVER repeat the same topic, phrase structure, or sentence pattern across messages.
2. Most texts are SHORT. One line. Two lines max. Long texts are rare.
3. MOST texts are MUNDANE (adjusted for genre). Food plans, running late, gossip — or genre equivalents.
4. Each person has a COMPLETELY DIFFERENT texting voice.
5. Time of day matters. 2am texts differ from 10am texts.
6. People don't always respond to every point.
7. Typos and autocorrect happen occasionally.
8. Short replies are realistic (e.g., one-word acknowledgments, quick confirmations, brief reactions).
9. Keep this feeling like real phone behavior, not a screenplay: avoid speeches, over-explaining, and theatrical lines.
10. Contact intensity must vary by relationship: some threads are sparse and utilitarian, others are chatty; do NOT make all contacts equally active.
11. If a plan/meetup is mentioned, prefer one concrete place name (venue/store/street/intersection) over vague placeholders.
12. Keep details selective. Do NOT dump many examples in one message or force culture markers unnaturally.
13. Keep reveals readable in hindsight: in-the-moment ambiguity is fine, but include enough breadcrumbs that a reader can infer what happened.
14. Use STRAIGHT QUOTES only (' and "), never curly quotes.
15. Stay CONSISTENT with the Story Bible and Character Arcs above.

